"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448582","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-05","<p>The Government maintains that £95,000 is a significant amount of money for anyone to be receiving for an exit, while the large majority of exit payments are already significantly below the level of the cap. Voluntary redundancy and workforce restructuring is not contingent upon access to six-figure exit payments. As such, we do not expect the cap to have a widespread impact on the take-up of voluntary redundancy, and believe the cap will enable public sector employers to retain the tools to effectively make organisational changes to their workforce whilst offering those made redundant generous provisions for loss of employment.</p><p> </p><p>The consultation on the public sector exit payment cap ran from 31 July to 27 August 2015, and received over 4000 responses. These responses included representations from public sector organisations. The Government will publish draft regulations and invite comment on them in due course.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","24842","2016-02-05T14:03:27.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448582/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448582/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448582/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-28","Public Sector: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of the proposed public sector exit payments cap on public sector employers' flexibility to restructure their workforce.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","24751"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448583","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-04","<p>Higher Education Institutions have a legal duty under the Equality Act 2010 to provide reasonable adjustments for disabled students and to monitor their compliance with their Equality Act duties. The Equality Act 2010 (Specific Duties) Regulations 2011 require institutions to publish information as to their compliance with the general public sector equality duty.</p><p> </p><p>In those cases where a student is dissatisfied with the response from their higher education institution and have completed the institution’s formal complaints procedures, they can take their complaint to the Office of the Independent Adjudicator (OIA) for Higher Education. The OIA is independent of Government and publishes an annual report setting out its performance in handling unresolved student complaints. In providing remedies, the OIA aims to return students to the position they were in before their complaint. In appropriate circumstances this can include financial payments.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","24824","2016-02-04T14:28:59.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448583/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448583/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448583/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-28","Students: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of mechanisms by which a disabled student can challenge a failure to make reasonable adjustment under the Equality Act 2010 by a higher education institution.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","24823"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448584","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-04","<p>Higher Education Institutions have a legal duty under the Equality Act 2010 to provide reasonable adjustments for disabled students and to monitor their compliance with their Equality Act duties. The Equality Act 2010 (Specific Duties) Regulations 2011 require institutions to publish information as to their compliance with the general public sector equality duty.</p><p> </p><p>In those cases where a student is dissatisfied with the response from their higher education institution and have completed the institution’s formal complaints procedures, they can take their complaint to the Office of the Independent Adjudicator (OIA) for Higher Education. The OIA is independent of Government and publishes an annual report setting out its performance in handling unresolved student complaints. In providing remedies, the OIA aims to return students to the position they were in before their complaint. In appropriate circumstances this can include financial payments.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","24823","2016-02-04T14:28:59.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448584/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448584/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448584/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-28","Students: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how his Department plans to monitor whether higher education institutions comply with their duties under the Equality Act 2010 towards disabled students; and what remedies are available to such students in the event that an institution does not comply with those duties.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","24824"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448585","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-02","<p>The Government consulted on implementing a public sector exit payment cap in July 2015. The Government response to this consultation was published on 16 September 2015. This response provides detail on which organisations and types of payments the Government intends to capture within the scope of the public sector exit payment cap. This accords with the Government’s manifesto commitment to end tax payer funded six figure payoffs for public sector workers.</p><p>The response document can be found at the following link: https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/464367/Public_sector_exit_payments_response.pdf</p><p>The exit payment cap will apply to payments made as a result of an employee leaving their employment. It will <strong>not</strong> affect any pension a person has earned through their years of service or have any impact on accrued pension rights or pension lump sum entitlements on retirement. It will capture contributions, made by the employer, to fund early access to an unreduced or partially reduced pension. This is because such costs are ultimately funded by the tax payer.</p><p>The Government has been clear that early retirements relating to ill health are outside the scope of the cap and will not be affected. Additionally, any payments directed by a Court or Tribunal will not be included in the scope of the cap.</p><p>Exits on compassionate grounds are not such a clearly defined concept as exits related to ill health or redundancy. There will generally be a large degree of employer discretion on the terms of such exits, and on any payments. In these cases there will be discretion available to relax the cap in individual cases, subject to relevant Ministerial or local council approval, as will be set out in further detail in forthcoming Treasury guidance and directions.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","24767","2016-02-02T17:28:20.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448585/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448585/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448585/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-28","Public Sector: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, which public sector organisations will not be covered by the public sector exit payments cap proposed in the Enterprise Bill.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","24793"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448586","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-02","<p>The Government made a manifesto commitment to end six-figure payouts in the public sector and wants to do so as soon as possible. These payments cost around £2 billion a year and it is important that they are fair, proportionate and provide value for money to the taxpayer that funds them. As such, the Government does not see any case for transitional arrangements to delay ending six-figure exit payments. However, the power for Ministers to relax the restrictions imposed by the cap provides the flexibility to do so in appropriate circumstances.</p><p> </p><p>Automatic indexing would fail to offer the flexibility that the clause currently provides for. As it stands, the Government can amend the level of the cap to take into account all prevailing circumstances, and with the additional scrutiny of the affirmative resolution procedure in Parliament.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","24800","2016-02-02T17:50:35.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448586/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448586/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448586/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-28","Public Sector: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make it his policy to implement automatic indexing of the proposed public sector exit payment cap.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","24794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448587","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-05","<p>The Government maintains that £95,000 is a significant amount of money for anyone to be receiving for an exit, while the large majority of exit payments are already significantly below the level of the cap. Voluntary redundancy and workforce restructuring is not contingent upon access to six-figure exit payments. As such, we do not expect the cap to have a widespread impact on the take-up of voluntary redundancy, and believe the cap will enable public sector employers to retain the tools to effectively make organisational changes to their workforce whilst offering those made redundant generous provisions for loss of employment.</p><p> </p><p>The consultation on the public sector exit payment cap ran from 31 July to 27 August 2015, and received over 4000 responses. These responses included representations from public sector organisations. The Government will publish draft regulations and invite comment on them in due course.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","24751","2016-02-05T14:03:27.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448587/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448587/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448587/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-28","Public Sector: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will consult public sector organisations which would be affected by the proposed exit payment cap on the technical considerations of that cap.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","24842"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448588","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-20","<p>We are investing in apprenticeships to meet identified skill needs across all sectors. We are committed to reaching 3 million apprenticeship starts in England by 2020 and will ensure they deliver the skills employers and the economy need for growth. We have also announced plans for ground-breaking reforms to technical and professional education, working in direct partnership with employers to ensure the new system provides the skills most needed for the 21st century. Together with creating 5 National Colleges, supporting a new network of Institutes of Technology and rolling out more degree and higher level apprenticeships, we are helping to equip people with the higher and technical level skills that are in demand.</p><p>Our aim is for all local areas to take a leading role in skills provision to ensure it is responsive to local economic priorities and devolution deals with areas around the country are a big step towards this ambition so that they can secure the training and skills that local employers need.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-04-20T08:29:53.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448588/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448588/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448588/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-28","Vacancies: Skilled Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what recent consideration he has given to the findings of the UK Commission for Employment and Skills on the issue of skills shortage vacancies; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","24682"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448589","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-05","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 10 November 2015 to question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=14404" target="_blank">UIN 14404</a></p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-02-05T14:07:59.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448589/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448589/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448589/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-28","EU Globalisation Fund: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department plans to apply to the EU's Globalisation Adjustment Fund for funding for the UK steel industry.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","24713"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448590","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-04","<p>Data is not collected in the way the Hon Member has requested. The Office of the Independent Adjudicator has a key performance indicator which tracks cases closed within six months from the receipt of the complaint form. In its most recently published annual report, the Office of the Independent Adjudicator reported that 39 per cent of cases were closed within this period.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-02-04T15:02:43.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448590/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448590/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448590/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-28","Office of the Independent Adjudicator for Higher Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many cases heard by the Office of the Independent Adjudicator were closed within three months in (a) 2014 and (b) 2015.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","24689"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448591","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-03","<p>It is for the independent Commission to determine the timing for submitting its response to Government.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-02-03T12:11:15.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448591/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448591/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448591/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-28","Freedom of Information Act 2000","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 9 December 2015 to Question 902477, when he expects the Independent Commission on Freedom of Information to publish its review of the Freedom of Information Act 2000.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","24662"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448592","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-02","<p>There are a broad range of charitable trusts and foundations working in this area, including Action Against Addiction, Mind and the Lifeline Project. Institutional investors such as Big Society Capital and Bridges Ventures have a track record of investing in programmes focused upon tackling complex social problems of this type. We will be working closely with all of these stakeholders to ensure that the Life Chances Fund has a real impact in helping to tackle drug and alcohol addiction.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-02-02T15:58:38.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448592/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448592/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448592/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-28","Alcoholic Drinks and Drugs: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 26 January 2016 to Question 23621, which (a) charitable trusts and foundations, (b) institutional investors and (c) dedicated social impact funds have invested in drug and alcohol addiction.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","24673"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448593","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-02","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-02-02T09:07:41.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448593/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448593/answer","24654 FINAL.pdf","24654 FINAL.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - Prescription Drug Deaths","UKSA Letter to Member - Prescription Drug Deaths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448593/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-28","Prescription Drugs: Death","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, in how many deaths in the last two years consumption of an excess of prescription drugs was the primary cause.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","24654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448594","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-08","<p>The 2015 Autumn Statement announced over a billion pounds for NCS over the next parliament and the Government is committed to expanding the programme to 360,000 places by 2020. In 2013, the NCS Trust, an independent social enterprise, was established to manage NCS and deliver the programme. Cabinet Office is supporting the NCS Trust to develop their plans to meet this ambitious target and further details will be made available in due course.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-02-08T16:43:13.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448594/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448594/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448594/answer","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448594/answer/previousversion/42926","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-28","Voluntary Work: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will publish his plans for the future of the National Citizen Service.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","24655"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448595","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-04","<p>To remain the best in the world, the Civil Service needs to respond to both the challenges and opportunities of our times. The Civil Service continues to require new and different skills to respond to the fiscal environment, global competition and changes in technology, whilst at the same time delivering better services more efficiently: in short, doing more for less.</p><p>The numbers of civil servants affected by the Government’s action to end six figure pay outs in the public sector will depend upon the terms applicable when the staff leave and which staff are exited.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-02-04T09:33:20.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448595/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448595/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448595/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-28","Civil Servants: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what (a) number and (b) proportion of civil servants will be affected by the Government's proposed exit payment cap.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","24843"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448596","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-02","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-02-02T17:36:29.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448596/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448596/answer","24828 table FINAL.xlsx ; 24828 FINAL.pdf","24828 table FINAL.xlsx ; 24828 FINAL.pdf","Excel Table for Member ; UKSA Letter for Member - Constitutencies","Excel Table for Member ; UKSA Letter for Member - Constitutencies","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448596/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-28","Public Sector: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, which 100 constituencies have the highest proportion of public sector employees.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","24828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448597","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-02","<p>The Landfill Communities Fund (LCF) is a tax credit scheme into which landfill operators contribute voluntarily. Information on the impact of the changes to the LCF announced at Autumn Statement 2015 is set out in <em>Reform and value of the Landfill Communities Fund. </em>This document can be found here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/reform-and-value-of-the-landfill-communities-fund/reform-and-value-of-the-landfill-communities-fund" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/reform-and-value-of-the-landfill-communities-fund/reform-and-value-of-the-landfill-communities-fund</a></p><p> </p><p>The government has received representations from a number of waste operators on this issue. We are taking views into consideration and our priority is to ensure that the LCF operates effectively and encourages money to be spent in the communities that need it.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-02-02T14:57:20.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448597/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448597/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448597/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-28","Landfill Communities Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the capacity of landfill operators to pay 10 per cent of qualifying contributions under the Landfill Communities Fund; and if he will allow more flexibility in the sourcing of the match funding.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","24797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448598","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-02","<p>The Landfill Communities Fund (LCF) is a tax credit scheme into which landfill operators contribute voluntarily. The government does not generate estimates for the number of projects supported by the scheme each year. ENTRUST, the regulator of the LCF, publishes information about projects funded by the scheme. This information is available on their website at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.entrust.org.uk/environmental-bodies/project-search/" target="_blank">http://www.entrust.org.uk/environmental-bodies/project-search/</a></p><p> </p><p>Further information on the impact of the changes to the LCF announced at Autumn Statement 2015 is set out in <em>Reform and value of the Landfill Communities Fund. </em>This document can be found here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/reform-and-value-of-the-landfill-communities-fund/reform-and-value-of-the-landfill-communities-fund" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/reform-and-value-of-the-landfill-communities-fund/reform-and-value-of-the-landfill-communities-fund</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-02-02T14:59:11.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448598/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448598/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448598/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-28","Landfill Communities Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the impact of the proposed changes to the Landfill Communities Fund on the number of community projects supported by that Fund each year.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","24796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448599","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-05","<p>Tax Reliefs</p><p> </p><p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) publishes the Exchequer cost for around 180 reliefs in its annual publication on the cost of tax reliefs. This list includes reliefs provided to both individuals and households as well as businesses.</p><p> </p><p>The data for the years 2012-13 to 2015-16 was published on 31 December 2015 and a link is provided below:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tax-expenditures-and-ready-reckoners" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tax-expenditures-and-ready-reckoners</a></p><p> </p><p>The data for the years 2010-11 and 2011-12 were published in December 2011 and 2012 and a link is provided below:</p><p><a href="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20121103081415/http:/hmrc.gov.uk/stats/tax_expenditures/menu.htm" target="_blank">http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20121103081415/http://hmrc.gov.uk/stats/tax_expenditures/menu.htm</a></p><p> </p><p><a href="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20130103073027/http:/hmrc.gov.uk/statistics/expenditures.htm" target="_blank">http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20130103073027/http://hmrc.gov.uk/statistics/expenditures.htm</a></p><p> </p><p>Public Spending Grants and Subsidies</p><p> </p><p>Information on ‘subsidies to private sector companies’ is published in Public Expenditure Statistical Analyses. A link is provided below:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/public-expenditure-statistical-analyses-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/public-expenditure-statistical-analyses-2015</a></p><p> </p><p>Table 2.1 on budgetary expenditure by economic category of spend includes this category on page 40 under ‘resource budgets’. Information is published for the last five outturn years.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-02-05T14:10:59.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448599/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448599/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448599/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-28","Business: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will publish the annual cost to the to the Exchequer of all subsidies and reliefs for business in the financial years 2010 to 2015.","false","Biography information for Stephen McPartland","Stevenage","Stephen McPartland","24787"
