nt year.</p><p> </p><p>The latest quarterly Home Office immigration statistics on entry clearance visas are published in ‘<em>Immigration</em><em> Statistics, July-September 2015</em>’, available from the Library of the House and from the Home Office website at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-statistics</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-02-10T17:24:30.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448727/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448727/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448727/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448727/answer/previousversion/42801","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-28","Visas: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many applications by Syrian nationals resident in Syria for UK visitor visas have been (a) received and (b) granted in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr David Jones","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","24708"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448728","Home Office","false","2016-02-04","<p>Border Force Officers will refer any passengers that require medical attention in accordance with established procedures and advice from Public Health England.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-02-04T15:40:20.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448728/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448728/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448728/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-28","Zika Virus: Disease Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps are being taken at border controls to prevent the Zika virus entering the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","24759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448729","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-04","<p>The Global Goals will be the starting point for all DFID’s work in the coming years. All DFID programmes have to consider at the design stage what longer-term impact they will have and how the envisaged benefits of the programme will be sustained beyond the period of DFID's support, and all individual DFID programmes and DFID's overall portfolio are reviewed on a regular basis, with the rate of progress towards the Global Goals a key factor.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-02-04T14:13:21.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448729/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448729/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448729/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-01-28","International Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what the implications are for the timescale of projects her Department funds in developing countries of the 15 year timescale that has been set for achieving the sustainable development goals.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","24754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448730","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-04","<p>Malawi has one of the highest rates of inflation in Africa: double digit inflation is commonplace. High inflation, alongside high fiscal deficits, debt and interest rates, are lowering business confidence and crowding out private investment. Social services are being delivered from a constrained budget with high levels of government borrowing. Poor harvests in 2015 and poor rainfall due to the ongoing El Nino are affecting the national economy and Malawi is now facing its worst food insecurity crisis in a decade. The UK and international partners are responding.</p><p>DFID Malawi works closely with other development partners, in particular the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund (IMF), to monitor the macroeconomic situation in Malawi. The IMF’s Article IV Consultation in December 2015 concluded that <em>“an appropriately tight fiscal policy is needed to support monetary policy actions aimed at placing inflation on a downward trajectory.”</em> DFID is working with the World Bank to inform the Government of Malawi’s next Development Strategy.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-02-04T15:58:36.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448730/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448730/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448730/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-01-28","Malawi: Inflation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the effect of high inflation in Malawi.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","24743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448731","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-04","<p>DFID has a significant programme of ongoing support in health, education, agriculture, water and sanitation and economic development, particularly in rural areas and with the private sector, for growth, jobs, incomes and food insecurity. We support increasing access to justice for women and vulnerable groups, accountability and governance reforms.</p><p>The UK was one of the first development partners to respond to Malawi’s international appeal for emergency aid in October 2015. The UK has now committed £14.5m through partners including the World Food Programme, UNICEF and an International Non-Governmental Organisation (INGO) consortium led by Save the Children. This support includes:</p><ul><li>Food for over 800,000 people, including pre-positioning of food, nutrition supplies and livestock vaccines.</li><li>Cash transfers for up to 450,000 people who live near functioning markets but do not have the means to purchase food</li><li>Mass screening of up to 800,000 children to identify urgent nutritional support needs</li><li>Specialist supplies for up to 75,000 children and others suffering from acute malnutrition</li><li>Vital protection support to vulnerable people, including women and girls, in displacement and refugee camps</li></ul>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-02-04T15:58:57.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448731/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448731/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448731/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-01-28","Malawi: Malnutrition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to address the prevalence of hunger in Malawi.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","24744"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448732","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-04","<p>The Government will provide £5.8 billion over the next five years to support developing countries in tackling climate change through the UK International Climate Fund, including at least £1.76 billion in 2020, ensuring that the UK plays its part in achieving the goal of mobilising $100 billion of climate finance a year by 2020. We plan to spend 50% of our climate finance on adaptation and 50% on mitigation.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-02-04T15:59:21.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448732/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448732/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448732/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-01-28","Developing Countries: Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what plans the Government has to contribute to the funding agreed at the Paris Climate Conference in December 2015 to assist developing countries in adapting to the effects of climate change.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","24753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448733","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-02","<p>This information could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-02-02T17:19:52.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448733/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448733/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448733/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-28","Legal Aid Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what costs in each category of expenditure his Department incurred in relation to the proposed tender of criminal legal aid contracts.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","24764"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448734","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-05","<p>Data on the confiscation of all types of weapons for the period requested could only be provided at disproportionate cost. I refer the Hon Member to PQ24706, which contains data on firearms, and PQ24558, which contains data on knives.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-02-05T12:32:58.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448734/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448734/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448734/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-28","Prisons: Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what information his Department holds on the number of weapons confiscated at each UK prison for each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","24790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448735","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-05","<p>The Ministry of Justice is one of the largest government departments and has responsibility for a number of different parts of the justice system - the courts, tribunals, prisons, legal services, youth justice, probation services, and attendance centres. The Department includes terms and conditions in its contracts that require third parties such as contracted-out services and suppliers (e.g. courier and postal services) to inform us of any data or security breaches that may have taken place. To identify any breaches involving document retention or security policies relating to confidential or secure materials by external consultants or other third parties that may have taken place would require a search across all the Department’s branches, which would incur a disproportionate cost.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-02-05T14:37:57.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448735/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448735/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448735/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-28","Ministry of Justice: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 28 January 2016 to Question 23485, for what reasons the information sought could only be provided at disproportionate cost; and what discussions his Department has had with other Government departments on holding this information in a way which permits its less costly provision.","false","Biography information for Stephen Phillips","Sleaford and North Hykeham","Stephen Phillips","24756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448736","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-05","<p>The eight apparent homicides occurred at the following prisons: HMP Dartmoor, HMP Doncaster, HMP Long Lartin, HMP Nottingham, HMP Peterborough, HMP Ranby, HMP Swaleside, HMP Wandsworth.</p><p>The classification of these deaths remains provisional until confirmed at inquest.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-02-05T14:44:36.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448736/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448736/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448736/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-28","Prisons: Homicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, in which prisons the eight apparent homicides referred to in the Safety in Custody Statistics, England and Wales: Deaths in prison custody to December 2015; Assaults and Self-harm to September 2015, published on 28 January 2016, took place.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","24862"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448737","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-02","<p>The action plan developed by South Yorkshire Community Rehabilitation Company in response to the operational assurance audit last year is commercially sensitive.</p><p>We hold providers rigorously to account for their performance and take action wherever they are falling short. Following an audit by the Ministry of Justice, South Yorkshire CRC has now developed an action plan. We will continue to monitor the CRC’s performance closely.</p><p>Our probation reforms are designed to make sure almost all offenders receive support on release, including, for the first time, those sentenced to less than 12 months.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-02-02T16:28:45.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448737/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448737/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448737/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-28","South Yorkshire Community Rehabilitation Company","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will place in the Library the improvement plan developed by South Yorkshire Community Rehabilitation Company in response to the audit conducted by his Department.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","24848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448738","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-02","<p>This Government wants people to resolve disputes away from court wherever possible, including through mediation which can be less stressful and more efficient. Between 1 October 2014 and 30 September 2015, public funding was provided for the first single session of family mediation where only one of the participants was eligible for legal aid in 6,022 cases. This is the latest 12-month period for which figures are available. Public funding became available on this basis during this period, on 3 November 2014. Figures are only available for cases that have completed and for which the bill has been submitted to the Legal Aid Agency by the mediation provider.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-02-02T17:17:36.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448738/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448738/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448738/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-28","Mediation: Family Proceedings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, in how many cases funding has been provided for the first single session of family mediation where one of the participants qualifies for legal aid in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","24670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448739","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-02","<p>My Rt Hon friend, the Secretary of State for Justice, has a clear set of priorities for the Ministry of Justice. These priorities are regularly reviewed.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-02-02T16:22:59.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448739/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448739/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448739/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-28","Ministry of Justice: Departmental Responsibilities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what plans he has to review his Department's priorities in the next six months.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","24735"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448740","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-02","<p>Data on confiscation of weapons of all types for the period requested could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>The table below shows the number of real firearms found in prison over the 5 year period requested. In contrast there were 15 such incidents over the 5 year period from 2006 to 2010.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="6"><p><strong>Firearms reported on the Incident Reporting System (IRS)<sup>1,2</sup>, 2011 to 2015</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Firearm description</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Real (Functional)<sup>3</sup></p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Real (Non-Functional)<sup>4</sup></p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>0</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>0</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="6"><p>(1) Includes NOMS operated Immigration Removal Centres.</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="6"><p>(2) Excludes finds of toy guns or home-made replicas and imitation guns.</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="6"><p>(3) “Functional firearms” were: a Taser mistakenly brought into a prison by police; youths shooting rabbits on prison grounds external to the prison; a CS Gas canister discovered in prisoner property sent in from court; a gun discovered in a bag brought in by a visitor.</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="6"><p>(4) “Non-functional” firearm was found in a prison building outside the prison walls.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-02-02T16:14:25.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448740/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448740/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448740/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-28","Prisons: Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many weapons have been confiscated in prisons in each year since 2010; and what the (a) number and (b) proportion of such weapons were firearms.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","24706"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448741","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-05","<p>The new Ministry of Justice (MoJ) appraisal system incorporates a guided distribution which sets the parameters for the number of <em>Outstanding, </em>performance markings. MoJ adopted a staggered approach to implementing the new cross government performance management system. Launch dates were as follows:</p><p> </p><ul><li>MoJ HQ, agencies Arms Length Bodies (excluding National Offender Management Service (NOMS) and National Probation Service (NPS)) - April 2013</li><li>NOMS - April 2014</li><li>NPS - June 2014</li></ul><p>Please note that the term <em>Outstanding</em> was not used across all MoJ business groups prior to the introduction of the new system.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2010-2011</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011-12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012-13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013-14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014-15</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Top Performance Management Review Markings Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>11587</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>10892</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>9100</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>9252</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>7580</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-02-05T14:30:57.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448741/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448741/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448741/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-28","Ministry of Justice: Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Justice of 26 January 2016, Official Report, column 129, how many staff in his Department were given an end-of-year appraisal rating of outstanding in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","24663"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448742","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-05","<p>The Treasury sets public sector pay policy, which includes the 1% cap, in line with wider government priorities. This policy has been subject to agreement with the Prime Minister and consultation within the government at Ministerial level.</p><p>In line with the pay freeze announced by the Government in the June Budget 2010, the pay of staff employed by the Ministry of Justice in 2011-12 and 2012-13 earning a full time equivalent of £21,000 or less received pay increases of up to £250. MoJ exited the pay freeze on 1 August 2013. Since then MOJ staff received pay awards averaging at 1% each year, in line with the Government policy.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","24665","2016-02-05T14:16:57.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448742/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448742/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448742/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-28","Public Sector: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Justice of 26 January 2016, Official Report, column 129, what discussions he has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on lifting the one per cent public sector pay cap.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","24664"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448743","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-05","<p>The Treasury sets public sector pay policy, which includes the 1% cap, in line with wider government priorities. This policy has been subject to agreement with the Prime Minister and consultation within the government at Ministerial level.</p><p>In line with the pay freeze announced by the Government in the June Budget 2010, the pay of staff employed by the Ministry of Justice in 2011-12 and 2012-13 earning a full time equivalent of £21,000 or less received pay increases of up to £250. MoJ exited the pay freeze on 1 August 2013. Since then MOJ staff received pay awards averaging at 1% each year, in line with the Government policy.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","24664","2016-02-05T14:16:57.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448743/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448743/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448743/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-28","Ministry of Justice: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Justice of 26 January 2016, Official Report, column 129, what pay rise in percentage terms, in each salary band in his Department, staff have received in each financial year since 2010-11.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","24665"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448744","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-02","<p>Statistics for assaults on staff by prison are published on an annual basis by calendar year in the Safety in Custody statistics bulletin annual assaults tables (see table 3.15 at the link below). <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/495430/safety-in-custody-assaults-dec-2014.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/495430/safety-in-custody-assaults-dec-2014.xls</a>. Figures for 2015 are due for publication in April 2016.</p><p>Statistics for serious assaults on staff by prison are due for release on in April 2016 as part of the Safety in Custody statistics bulletin annual assaults tables. This publication will include breakdowns of serious assaults on staff by prison in each calendar year.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","24676","2016-02-02T15:10:29.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448744/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448744/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448744/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-28","Prisons: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, in which prisons the 4,568 assaults on staff took place, set out in the Safety in Custody Summary Statistics, England and Wales, deaths to 12 months ending December 2015, assaults and self-harm to 12 months ending September 2015, published in January 2016.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","24675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448745","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-02","<p>Statistics for assaults on staff by prison are published on an annual basis by calendar year in the Safety in Custody statistics bulletin annual assaults tables (see table 3.15 at the link below). <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/495430/safety-in-custody-assaults-dec-2014.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/495430/safety-in-custody-assaults-dec-2014.xls</a>. Figures for 2015 are due for publication in April 2016.</p><p>Statistics for serious assaults on staff by prison are due for release on in April 2016 as part of the Safety in Custody statistics bulletin annual assaults tables. This publication will include breakdowns of serious assaults on staff by prison in each calendar year.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","24675","2016-02-02T15:10:30.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448745/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448745/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448745/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-28","Prisons: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, in which prisons the 595 serious assaults on staff took place, set out in the Safety in Custody Summary Statistics, England and Wales, deaths to 12 months ending December 2015, assaults and self-harm to 12 months ending September 2015, published in January 2016.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","24676"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448746","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-02-02","<p>I have been asked to reply on behalf of the Home Office who are the lead Department.</p><p> </p><p>The British-Irish Council facilitates and fosters collaboration among member administrations and provides a forum where issues, such as substance misuse, can be discussed. The use and misuse of alcohol was the theme of the British-Irish Council Ministerial Summit hosted by the Irish Government in June 2015 on which the following communiqué was issued: <a href="http://www.britishirishcouncil.org/sites/default/files/communiqu%C3%A9s/24%20-%20Twenty%20Fourth%20Summit%20-%20Dublin%20-%2019%20June%202015.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.britishirishcouncil.org/sites/default/files/communiqu%C3%A9s/24%20-%20Twenty%20Fourth%20Summit%20-%20Dublin%20-%2019%20June%202015.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2016-02-02T17:11:47.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448746/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448746/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448746/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-01-28","Alcoholic Drinks: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what progress is being made through the British-Irish Council on tackling alcohol misuse throughout the British Isles.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","24668"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448747","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-05","<p>The Government has continuously made compensation available under the War Pensions Scheme for injuries, illness or disease caused by service before 6 April 2005, including mesothelioma. On 11 January 2016 (Official Report, column 612-613) I informed the House that 11 April 2016 would be the earliest date from which we could provide the option of a lump sum payment to Service veterans diagnosed with mesothelioma on or after 16 December 2015. If an accepted claim is concluded before 11 April 2016 and the individual has opted for a lump sum, payment of a War Disablement Pension and any supplementary allowances will begin in the normal way until the lump sum can be paid. The lump sum will be reduced to reflect the amounts paid until that point. If a claimant who has signed an option form to receive the lump sum dies before 11 April 2016 the lump sum will be paid to the veteran's designated recipient.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-02-05T12:51:33.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448747/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448747/answer","20160111_Hansard_extract_on_Armed_Forces_Bill.docx","20160111_Hansard_extract_on_Armed_Forces_Bill.docx","20160111 - Hansard extract on Armed Forces Bill","20160111 - Hansard extract on Armed Forces Bill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448747/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-28","Veterans: Mesothelioma","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if the Prime Minister will take steps to speed up the legal process for cases involving ex-service personnel who have contracted mesothelioma; and if he will consider awarding equal compensation to the relatives of service personnel who have died while the process is ongoing.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","24684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448748","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-02","<p>The Solicitors Regulation Authority (SRA) has been conducting a wide-ranging investigation into two firms - Leigh Day &amp; Co, and Public Interest Lawyers - as a result of concerns about their conduct in the Al-Sweady Inquiry and associated litigation. Among other things, it is investigating how these firms obtain instructions from claimants in Iraq - a matter that is directly relevant to the unprecedented number of allegations with which the Iraq Historic Allegations Team is contending.</p><p>The Government welcomes the SRA's decision to refer Leigh Day &amp; Co to the Solicitors Disciplinary Tribunal, and awaits its decision with regard to Public Interest Lawyers. We will decide what further action may be appropriate in the light of the results of this process.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-02-02T15:54:23.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448748/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448748/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448748/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-28","Iraq Historic Allegations Team","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the government has initiated legal action against any law firms for abuse of the Iraq Historic Allegations Team inquiry.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","24774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448749","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-05","<p>The Department negotiated a Direct Award with Stagecoach to provide services until March 2018. The new Franchise document is currently being prepared for publication and will be available soon on our website at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/public-register-of-rail-passenger-franchise-agreements" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/public-register-of-rail-passenger-franchise-agreements</a>.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-02-05T10:13:40.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448749/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448749/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448749/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-28","East Midlands Trains","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will publish the East Midlands Trains Franchise Extension document to March 2018.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","24680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448750","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-05","<p>The number of passenger accidents over the years 2011 to 2015 that involved slam-door stock, broken down by injury degree, is set out in the table below:-</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Degree of Injury</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Major</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Minor</p></td><td><p>19</p></td><td><p>17</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>15</p></td><td><p>20</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Shock/trauma</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total accidents</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>19</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>17</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>10</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>21</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-02-05T10:24:23.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448750/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448750/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448750/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-28","Railways: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many accidents have occurred on trains involving slam doors in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","North East Somerset","Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","24740"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448751","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-05","<p>2 cases were reported by Shared Services Arvato</p><p>2 cases were reported by GBGroup plc</p><p>2 cases were reported by Pearson</p><p>1 case was reported by Scottish Qualifications Authority (SQA)</p><p>1 case was reported by Civil Service Resourcing who reported non-receipt of documents from the sender.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-02-05T12:21:23.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448751/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448751/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448751/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-28","Department for Transport: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 28 January 2016 to Question 23487, which external consultants or other third parties were responsible for the eight breaches there identified.","false","Biography information for Stephen Phillips","Sleaford and North Hykeham","Stephen Phillips","24830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448752","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-05","<p>Of the eight breaches reported pursuant to the answer of 28 January 2016 to Question 23487 none of them concerned documents prior to April 2014</p><p> </p><p>Since April 2014;</p><ul><li>6 cases concerned OFFICIAL or OFFICIAL-SENSITIVE documents</li><li>2 cases did not involve documents</li></ul>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-02-05T12:26:08.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448752/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448752/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448752/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-28","Department for Transport: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 28 January 2016 to Question 23487, of the eight breaches there identified, how many concerned documents within each of the following categories applicable prior to April 2014, namely (a) top secret, (b) secret, (c) confidential, (d) restricted, (e) protected and (f) unclassified; and how many breaches concerned documents within each of the following categories applicable from April 2014, namely (i) top secret, (ii) secret and (iii) official-sensitive or official.","false","Biography information for Stephen Phillips","Sleaford and North Hykeham","Stephen Phillips","24831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448753","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-02","<p>The 2015 Spending Review settlement confirmed that the Government will be providing around £11 billion of support to Transport for London (TfL) over the period from 2015/16 to 2020/21. In determining the overall amount of support for TfL, my Department and HM Treasury took into account a wide range of factors, including TfL’s likely income from rail fares.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-02-02T15:32:54.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448753/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448753/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448753/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-28","Railways: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much his Department's financial contribution is to Transport for London related to its decision to raise the cost of regulated rail fares in London by the rate of the Retail Price Index.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","24776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448754","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-02","<p>If the hon Member contacts my departmental office I would of course be happy to consider his request in the normal way.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-02-02T14:40:10.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448754/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448754/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448754/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-28","Manchester Metrolink","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will meet the hon. Member for Oldham West and Royton and local authority officials to discuss the proposal for an Ashton Loop Line and Middleton Spur extension to Greater Manchester's Metrolink tram system.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","24806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448755","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-02","<p>The Office of Rail and Road’s Final Determination for Control Period 5<sup><sup>[1]</sup></sup> assumed that Network Rail would spend £12.1bn on renewals between 2014-2019. Network Rail is reviewing its plans for the coming financial year and will publish an updated Delivery Plan in March containing detailed forward plans for the delivery of operations, maintenance and renewals up to 2019.</p><p> </p><p><sup><sup>[1]</sup></sup> http://orr.gov.uk/publications/reports/final-determination</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-02-02T14:31:42.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448755/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448755/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448755/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-28","Railways: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the statement on page 1 of Network Rail's report, Replanning the Investment Programme, published on 25 November 2015, that there will be a reduction in renewals activity in Control Period 5, what renewal works Network Rail intends to defer into Control Period 6; and what the planned expenditure was on those works in Control Period 5.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","24854"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448756","Women and Equalities","false","2016-02-02","<p>I am working closely with the Cabinet Office to modernise recruitment practices and attract a more diverse field of candidates from an ever-wider range of social and professional backgrounds.</p><p>This includes engaging with government departments, the private sector and a range of different diversity networks and groups. We have engaged with them through online advertising, social media and at events to promote and raise awareness of public appointments and better understand the barriers or concerns for those considering a public appointment.</p><p>The most recent figures published show that we are making real, consistent, progress in increasing the number of public appointments going to women. Last financial year 44% of new appointments were made to women.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-02-02T17:54:20.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448756/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448756/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448756/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-01-28","Females: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, how many meetings she has had on increasing the number of women receiving public appointments since May 2015.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","24805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448757","Women and Equalities","false","2016-02-02","<p>Eliminating the gender pay gap is a key priority for this government. We will shortly seek views on the draft regulations requiring large private and voluntary sector employers in Great Britain to publish information about differences in the pay and bonuses paid to male and female employees. The government wants to commence these regulations at the earliest opportunity. We have also pledged to extend these requirements to the public sector. Public bodies will be covered by different regulations, following a further consultation that we will issue soon.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","24679","2016-02-02T15:01:48.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448757/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448757/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448757/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-01-28","Equal Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what the Government's timetable is for introducing measures to place a duty on larger employers to publish information about bonuses paid to men and women as part of their gender pay gap reporting.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","24678"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448758","Women and Equalities","false","2016-02-02","<p>Eliminating the gender pay gap is a key priority for this government. We will shortly seek views on the draft regulations requiring large private and voluntary sector employers in Great Britain to publish information about differences in the pay and bonuses paid to male and female employees. The government wants to commence these regulations at the earliest opportunity. We have also pledged to extend these requirements to the public sector. Public bodies will be covered by different regulations, following a further consultation that we will issue soon.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","24678","2016-02-02T15:01:48.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448758/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448758/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448758/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-01-28","Equal Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what the Government's timetable is for introducing measures to implement a gender pay gap reporting among (a) public sector, (b) private sector and (c) voluntary sector employees.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","24679"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448759","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-05","<p>Table 1 shows the number of applications for Funeral Expenses Payments which were made and the number refused in the financial years 2010/11 to 2014/15.</p><p><strong>Table 1</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Applications (000)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Initial Refusals (000)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2010/11</strong></p></td><td><p>69</p></td><td><p>34</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011/12</strong></p></td><td><p>69</p></td><td><p>36</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p>66</p></td><td><p>34</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td><p>59</p></td><td><p>27</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014/15</strong></p></td><td><p>51</p></td><td><p>24</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Data sourced from the DWP policy, Budget and Management Information System and is published in the Annual Report by the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions on the Social Fund for the relevant year.</p><p>The budget for the Social Fund, Funeral Expenses Payment (FEP) expenditure is demand-led. Legislation prescribes that payments are made to all eligible applicants. That is people responsible for arranging a funeral who meet the rules on relationships with the deceased and receive a qualifying benefit. Provision for FEPs is made by central Government through the supply estimate process, but these figures are not translated into an operational budget and do not impact eligibility or award amounts.</p><p>In a minority of cases funeral expense payments are subsequently recovered from the deceased’s estate and in these cases the net amount can be very small. Given the small numbers involved it is not appropriate to release figures as there is a risk of identifying individuals.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-02-05T11:41:04.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448759/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448759/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448759/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-28","Funeral Payments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many applications for Social Fund funerals were made in each year between 2010 and 2015; how many such applications were refused; and what the (a) budget and (b) lowest payment made was.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","24696"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448760","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-01","<p>This measure does not apply until April 2018. We value the work of the supported housing sector extremely highly and are working closely with them to ensure they are supported as effectively as possible in advance of the police taking effect.</p><p>The Department alongside the Department for Communities and Local Government has jointly commissioned an evidence review of supported housing.</p><p>The results of this research will determine our future policy development and any appropriate exemptions.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-02-01T13:38:39.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448760/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448760/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448760/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-28","Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether (a) new or existing Housing Benefit claimants and (b) those in supported accommodation will have their allowance cut to Local Housing Allowance rates from 1 April 2016.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","24683"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448761","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-02","<p>The information you have requested is not readily available, and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost. All our sites fully comply with current legislation: Building Regulations, the Disability Discrimination Act and the Equalities Act 2010.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-02-02T10:21:56.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448761/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448761/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448761/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-28","Social Security Benefits: Medical Examinations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many venues where assessments for personal independence payments or employment and support allowance are carried out do not have (a) disabled parking facilities, (b) disabled access toilets, (c) a distance between the car park and the venue of 50 metres or less, (d) a ramp in addition to stairs to the entrance, where there are stairs; and for what reason it is not his Department's policy that such facilities must be provided at assessment centres.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","24736"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448762","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-02","<p>Section 3.10 of the Revised WCA Handbook for healthcare professionals states that prognosis advice &quot;refers to the time frame for when the claimant could be considered fit for work or fit for work-related activity.&quot;</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/work-capability-assessment-handbook-for-healthcare-professionals" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/work-capability-assessment-handbook-for-healthcare-professionals</a></p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-02-02T16:58:55.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448762/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448762/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448762/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-28","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 25 January 2016 to Question 23428, whether the prognosis statements issued after assessments for employment and support allowance are an indication of an assessment of the likelihood of improvement in the claimant's medical condition.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","24851"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448763","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-04","<p>The evidence review commissioned by the Department will work closely with charities, landlords stakeholders etc. and will look at the shape, scale and cost of the supported housing sector.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-02-04T12:05:52.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448763/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448763/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448763/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-28","Housing Benefit: Reviews","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the contribution made by the hon. Member for Great Yarmouth on 27 January 2015, Official Report, column 259, what the terms for the one year review of cuts to housing benefit will be.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","24778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448764","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-02","<p>Each case is considered separately and advice based on individual circumstances. Guidance for health professionals can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/work-capability-assessment-handbook-for-healthcare-professionals" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/work-capability-assessment-handbook-for-healthcare-professionals</a></p><p> </p><p>Because we run repeat assessments, which are important to ensure people are getting the right support, we can assess changes to claimants health conditions.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="5"><p>Volume of caseloads in thousands</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="5"><p>Outcomes of claims where repeat functional assessment has been completed</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="3"><p>Entitled to Employment and Support Allowance:</p></td><td rowspan="2"><p>Fit for Work</p></td><td rowspan="2"><p>Any outcome</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Work Related Activity Group</p></td><td><p>Support Group</p></td><td><p>Either group</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>All</p></td><td><p>501.3</p></td><td><p>666.9</p></td><td><p>1168.2</p></td><td><p>315.9</p></td><td><p>1484.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Other Medical Condition</p></td><td><p>500.8</p></td><td><p>665.8</p></td><td><p>1166.6</p></td><td><p>315.8</p></td><td><p>1482.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Parkinson’s Disease</p></td><td><p>0.5</p></td><td><p>1.1</p></td><td><p>1.6</p></td><td><p>0.1</p></td><td><p>1.7</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-02-02T17:34:14.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448764/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448764/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448764/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-28","Employment and Support Allowance: Parkinson's Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what criteria are used by healthcare professionals conducting employment and support allowance assessments to determine whether people with Parkinson's disease will be able to return to work within three, six, 12 or 18 months or two years; and how many employment and support allowance claimants with Parkinson's disease have had their health improve such that they are able to return to work.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","24850"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448765","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-02","<p>A process to automate the sharing of data between Universal Credit and Local Authorities to support applications to Local Council Tax Reduction Schemes will be implemented in the next month.</p><p>There are no plans to automate applications for Council Tax Reduction through Universal Credit. This must be done separately by the claimant with the Local Authority.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-02-02T10:16:54.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448765/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448765/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448765/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-28","Universal Credit: Council Tax Reduction Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer 27 January 2016 to Question 23759, whether there is scope for the Work Coach to pass on details of the claimant's universal credit application to their local authority in order to begin automatically the application for council tax reduction.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","24803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448766","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-05","<p>The Department for Health (DH) lead the Preventing Suicide in England Strategy and since 2014 have published two annual reports. The Department for Work and Pensions (DWP) has provided information to contribute to the annual reports, to address the guidance and training it provides for staff and the DWP and DH joint work to look at improving co-ordination of mental health and employment support services.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-02-05T15:46:56.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448766/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448766/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448766/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-28","Suicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what contribution his Department is making to the delivery and monitoring of the Preventing Suicide in England strategy with specific reference to people identified as being vulnerable due to social and economic circumstances.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","24847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448767","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-02","<p>In October 2014, the Department for Work and Pensions published guidance for Government officials on how the Test should be applied when formulating policy. Produced in collaboration with third sector partners from the Relationship Alliance, the guidance outlines the basis for the Family Test and provides policy officials with information on how the Test can be applied.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-02-02T16:54:44.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448767/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448767/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448767/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-28","Department for Work and Pensions: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what guidance his Department has prepared for government departments on implementing the Family Test.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","24858"
